TY  - GEN
T1  - Exploring autoethnography as a method for understanding sociocultural factors in medical education
AN  - 3231297319; 2039574011
AB  - Background: Medical education is a complex and multifaceted field, influenced by a variety of sociocultural factors. Understanding these factors is necessary to provide effective education and training for medical students. Autoethnography offers a unique perspective by examining the researcher's personal experiences within a cultural context. Objectives: This study aimed to explore the basis for and potential usefulness of autoethnography as a method for understanding sociocultural factors in medical education. Methods: By employing a descriptive-realistic approach, a 58 second year medical students at Alkindy College of Medicine were encouraged to describe their life experiences in narrative bases to provide accurate depictions of people, places, and things while minimizing character evaluation or judgment. This paper utilizes storytelling techniques to engage readers and provide insights into the world of the student. Upon reviewing the students' reports, we adapted descriptive criteria and evaluated the students' ability to effectively communicate their ideas and create a vivid picture for the reader. We also assessed the believability and plausibility of the events to ensure that the students were able to create a coherent and realistic context for their stories. Findings: Research showed that participants face challenges in expressing their thoughts and feelings and difficulty in maintaining privacy while discussing sensitive topics. On other hand, they gained an understanding of sociocultural factors that influence a student's experience of suffering. They recognized the importance of incorporating cultural sensitivity into their interactions with patients. This realization emphasized the necessity of actively listening to patients and showing empathy when they share their stories of suffering. The findings underscore the significance of the medical student's personal journey in shaping their professional development. Discussion: Integrating autoethnography into medical education at Al Kindy Medical College holds promise for creating a more inclusive and culturally sensitive learning environment, enriching students' cultural competency.
