TY  - GEN
T1  - Both Sides of the River: Aboriginal Experiences of Cardiology
AN  - 3217808936; 2039037797
AB  - Background: The enduring effects of colonisation drive disproportionately high rates of cardiovascular disease in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people. Despite this, only 0.1% of cardiologists are Indigenous. Method: Co-autoethnography, using narrative inquiry, was employed to analyse personal experiences during physician and cardiology training to identify factors contributing to our underrepresentation in the cardiology medical workforce and potential areas for improvement. Over several meetings, authors engaged in Yarning to generate data for analysis before an iterative writing process was undertaken with multiple review cycles. Results: Training challenges included racism, sexism, a lack of Indigenous supervisors and colleagues, the tension between biomedical and community expectations, and the broader invisibility of Indigenous peoples and culture within cardiology's medical system. The specialty’s low appeal among Indigenous doctors likely results from poor work-life balance during training and its rigid, hierarchical structure, which has been slow to integrate Indigenous ways of knowing, being, and doing. Interpretation: Potential opportunities for improvement include: expanding university education to better represent Indigenous perspectives and worldviews, mandatory cardiology advanced training placements at hospitals serving high numbers of Indigenous patients, more flexible training options and leave allocations, and comprehensive anti-racist training that transparently addresses the colonial history of Australia and its medical system. Conclusion: These personal experiences demonstrate the urgent need to improve cardiology for Indigenous health professionals, ultimately optimising cultural safety for Indigenous patients and consumers.
