TY  - JOUR
T1  - EEG-Neurofeedback-Informed Empathic Listening (Spiritual) Approach to Psychiatric Assessments: Exploratory Case Series Study
AN  - 3163552289; 646355981
AB  - Background: Empathic listening (EL) is emphasized in psychiatry but lacks structured training or evidence-based frameworks. This study introduces the mindfulness-to-transcendence (MT) framework and explores EEG-based validation for EL in psychiatric practice. Methodology: Three clinical and three classrooms based EL interactions were analyzed using autoethnography and portable EEG devices to study mindfulness and self-transcendence in psychiatrists and subjects. Results: Subjects (mean age 38.86 years) completed EL sessions (mean duration: ∼32 minutes). EEG recordings revealed gamma-predominant spikes in both subjects and psychiatrists, reflecting self-transcendence. A lagged synchronization of gamma activity (1-3 minutes) highlighted the role of EL in fostering emotional regulation, self-reflection, and healing. Conclusion: EL, supported by EEG evidence, enhances mindfulness and self-transcendence, promoting healing in psychiatry. The findings advocate incorporating EL training into psychiatric curricula for holistic patient care.
