TY  - GEN
T1  - AUTOETHNOGRAPHY: TESTIMONIO OF A LATINA NAVIGATING GRADUATE SCHOOL AND ADDICTION RESEARCH
AN  - 3094506494; 2034043785
AB  - Background: Patients have better health outcomes across the span of their mental health disorders when their provider comes from a similar cultural background to their own, yet less than 20% of drug counselors in the US are Hispanic/Latinx. An even smaller percent are doctoral-level clinical psychologists. Therefore, it is imperative to assess potential barriers to entry and identify methods that facilitate the increased representation of Hispanic/Latinx in substance use mental health counseling. Methods: Using an autoethnographic methodology, I analyzed my own educational trajectory as a Latina doctoral student in clinical psychology studying substance use and mental health. I identified the need for Hispanic/Latinx role models and mentors, a lack of exposure in both academic coursework and in clinical training, unique barriers for non-traditional, low socioeconomic status, bicultural Latina students, as well as how to remain “de pie” (standing) against all odds (i.e., university closure, COVID-19) to complete a doctorate. Results: Grounded in my educational biography, testimonios frame my research perspective to interrogate the role that educational institutions play in the professional development of Latina clinical researchers. Using my observations, reflective experiences and multiple intersectionalities, I am an advocate and an agent of change in the fight against health disparities and cultural sensitive practices for Hispanic/Latinx diagnosed with substance use disorders. I used my cultural values, emotional experiences, and struggles to find the meaning behind my testimonio and decipher my new professional identity. With the aim to search for better mental health care for marginalized communities and educational equity, I used my story to describe my journey, identify new ways to approach these relevant cultural issues, and raise awareness of the specific needs of these populations. Discussion: The results of this autoethnography identified areas of struggles and success in one Latina’s journey to becoming a clinician and researcher. Through this analysis, I describe my lived experiences to empower other Latina professionals and examine their own journey, provide recommendations, and inspire them to tell their stories. This reflective process provides an insight of how and why I decided to become a clinical psychologist and an addiction researcher against many challenges and explores many of the “behind the scenes” processes that happened throughout my journey.
