TY  - JOUR
T1  - PRESENTER 2
AN  - 2826439169; 641541220
AB  - Background: Following the global prohibition of 3,4-methylenedioxymethamphetamine (MDMA) in the 1980s, research into its therapeutic efficacy recommenced in 2001. About 20 years later, the results of the first phase 3 clinical trial of MDMA-assisted psychotherapy for posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) were published. Yet clinical research into MDMA only commenced in Australia in 2022. Objectives: To describe our journey to establish research into MDMA-assisted psychotherapy in Australia, which began in 2010. In doing so, we aim to provide the audience with an understanding of some of the current challenges in the provision of this novel treatment modality. Methods: Autoethnography and case studies from a clinical trial of MDMA-assisted psychotherapy. Findings: The process for achieving all the State and Federal approvals for a trial of this nature is complex and lengthy. Barriers to approval were social, or based on the opinion of a sole power holder within an Australian university context. Once the trial was approved to commence, it was important to be conscious of the Pollan effect and properly understand how the expectations of clinicians, the research team and participants might influence or interfere with the study. Conclusion: MDMA-assisted psychotherapy shows promise and clinical trials of MDMA-assisted psychotherapy are now commencing in Australia; however, there are barriers to the provision of this treatment outside of clinical research.
