TY  - JOUR
T1  - Reflections of the intersection of sport medicine and athletes with physical impairment
AN  - 1904037480; 616476808
AB  - Purpose: The purpose is to explore the intersection of sport medicine with the social model of disability. Consideration will be given to larger cultural and social realities within the Paralympic movement that influence para-sport medicine and disability, including how impaired bodies are understood and managed in medicalized spaces. Methodology: Qualitative inquiry, autoethnographic methodology, critical disability lens. Participants: Researcher as subject. Methods: In order to examine the intersection of sport medicine and physical impairment, I drew upon my 20 years as a sport physiotherapist and involvement with Paralympic sport. I maintained a reflexive journal regarding my protracted experience with Paralympic sport in Canada and abroad. Using a self ethnographic approach, I chronicled my story of Paralympic experiences, prompted by a variety of stimulus: when spectating sport, when consuming media about Paralympic athletes and para-sport events, when socializing with peers within the Paralympic community. Analysis included coding to identify recurrent and significant words, phrases or themes. The process was iterative, utilizing field notes to guide analysis and to facilitate further data collection. Analysis and interpretation of the data was conducted until elastic saturation was reached and the research question was addressed. Results: The telling and analysis of my Paralympic-sportmedicine story revealed the often subtle but very real tensions that challenge the practice of sport medicine and athletes with physical impairment. Medicalization of impairment, discomfort with obvious physical difference and the management of impaired bodies as biological phenomenon persist within the sport medicine community, preventing sport medicine practitioners from understanding and engaging with the lived experience of the para-sport athlete. Conclusions: Autoethnography or self narrative can privilege voices and experiences of people and cultures that often go unheard. It is my hope that my experience of the Paralympic community will contribute a small, very specific understanding of the social, biological and cultural nexus of disability and sport medicine.
