TY  - JOUR
T1  - An auto-ethnographic study exploring the experience of brain injury and the impact of rehabilitation on the process of recovery
AN  - 1013588816; 70731493
AB  - Objectives: The overarching aim of this auto-ethnographic study was to better understand the lived experience of brain injury and the impact rehabilitation can have on the recovery process of an individual. Potentially this could provide valuable evidence for clinicians working in the field of neurological rehabilitation who wish to gain further insight into their client's perspectives and perceptions. It is intended that this research will add to the current body of knowledge pertaining to the subjective value and meaning of rehabilitation for individuals following brain injury. The objectives of this piece of research were therefore, (a) to explore the experience of sustaining and living with a brain injury, (b) to explore the subjective experience of the rehabilitation process from the individual's perspective and (c) to better understand the impact of rehabilitation on the recovery process. Methods: This qualitative study utilises an autoethnographic approach to explore both the experiences of the author and those of four other participants in an attempt to provide a better understanding of the subjective reality of living with a brain injury and the impact of rehabilitation on the process of recovery. Data generated in the form of semi structured interviews was analysed using an interpretive thematic analytical approach in order to gain a more detailed, in depth understanding of the topic and identify connections and relationships within the data. Through the use of auto-ethnography the author's own views and experiences of brain injury are integrated as an additional source of data. Results: Thematic mind maps were developed using raw data gathered during the interview process as a way of visually representing emerging themes within the research. These maps were then synthesised and a final thematic map presenting overarching themes was generated. The overarching themes included: (1) The lost duck, (2) Grieving for a life lost, (3) It changed my life forever and (4) Maybe I could help people like me. The study found participants experienced significant biographical disruption following their brain injury resulting in a loss of purpose and direction in life. Findings suggest those with experience of both brain injury and the rehabilitation process possess inside knowledge and invaluable insights. Conclusions: The study concludes that insights and experiences provided by those with brain injury can help inform practice for healthcare care professionals working in neurological rehabilitation and create the basis for a more generalised understanding of this cultural group. Finally, a link is identified between an individual's illness experiences and a resulting eagerness to help 'others of similarity'.
